## Welcome! Want to learn more? See two factoextra-related books at https://goo.gl/ve3WBa
# Funcin para remover outliers usando IQR
remove_outliers <- function(x) {
  qnt <- quantile(x, probs=c(.25, .75), na.rm=TRUE)
  H <- 1.5 * IQR(x, na.rm=TRUE)
  x[x < (qnt[1] - H)] <- NA
  x[x > (qnt[2] + H)] <- NA
  return(x)
}

movies_clean <- movies %>%
  select(popularity, budget, revenue, runtime, 
         genresAmount, productionCoAmount, 
         productionCountriesAmount, voteCount, 
         voteAvg, actorsAmount, 
         castWomenAmount, castMenAmount) %>%
  mutate(across(everything(), as.numeric)) %>%
  # Remover outliers
  mutate(across(everything(), remove_outliers)) %>%
  # Eliminar filas con NA
  na.omit()
## Warning: There were 2 warnings in `mutate()`.
## The first warning was:
##  In argument: `across(everything(), as.numeric)`.
## Caused by warning:
## ! NAs introduced by coercion
##  Run `dplyr::last_dplyr_warnings()` to see the 1 remaining warning.
movies_scaled <- scale(movies_clean)

set.seed(531) # Seed para reproducibilidad
wss <- numeric(12)  
for (k in 1:12) {
  km <- kmeans(movies_scaled, 
               centers = k, 
               nstart = 50,  
               iter.max = 50)  
  wss[k] <- km$tot.withinss
}
## Warning: Quick-TRANSfer stage steps exceeded maximum (= 274850)
p <- fviz_nbclust(movies_scaled, 
             kmeans, 
             method = "wss",
             k.max = 12,  
             nstart = 50,  
             iter.max = 50) +  
  labs(title = "Mtodo del Codo para Determinar k ptimo",
       x = "Nmero de Clusters (k)",
       y = "Suma total de cuadrados dentro de clusters") +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Quick-TRANSfer stage steps exceeded maximum (= 274850)
print(p)

wss_diff <- diff(wss) / wss[-length(wss)] * 100
print("\nReduccin porcentual en WSS para cada k adicional:")
## [1] "\nReduccin porcentual en WSS para cada k adicional:"
for(i in 1:length(wss_diff)) {
  cat(sprintf("De %d a %d clusters: %.2f%% de reduccin\n", 
              i, i+1, abs(wss_diff[i])))
}

Agrupamiento

# Usar el preprocesamiento del ejercicio 1
movies_clean <- movies %>%
  select(popularity, budget, revenue, runtime, 
         genresAmount, productionCoAmount, 
         productionCountriesAmount, voteCount, 
         voteAvg, actorsAmount, 
         castWomenAmount, castMenAmount) %>%
  mutate(across(everything(), as.numeric)) %>%
  mutate(across(everything(), remove_outliers)) %>%
  na.omit()
## Warning: There were 2 warnings in `mutate()`.
## The first warning was:
##  In argument: `across(everything(), as.numeric)`.
## Caused by warning:
## ! NAs introduced by coercion
##  Run `dplyr::last_dplyr_warnings()` to see the 1 remaining warning.
# Escalar los datos
movies_scaled <- scale(movies_clean)

# 1. K-means con k=4 (basado en el anlisis del codo previo)
set.seed(531)
kmeans_result <- kmeans(movies_scaled, 
                       centers = 4, 
                       nstart = 50,
                       iter.max = 50)
## Warning: Quick-TRANSfer stage steps exceeded maximum (= 274850)
# 2. Clustering Jerrquico
# Usar una muestra para el clustering jerrquico si el dataset es muy grande
set.seed(531)
sample_size <- min(1000, nrow(movies_scaled))
sample_indices <- sample(1:nrow(movies_scaled), sample_size)
movies_sample <- movies_scaled[sample_indices, ]

# Calcular matriz de distancias de la muestra
dist_matrix <- dist(movies_sample, method = "euclidean")
hclust_result <- hclust(dist_matrix, method = "ward.D2")
hclust_clusters <- cutree(hclust_result, k = 4)

# 3. Evaluar calidad de k-means
silhouette_kmeans <- silhouette(kmeans_result$cluster, 
                               dist(movies_scaled))
sil_score_kmeans <- mean(silhouette_kmeans[,3])

# 4. Evaluar calidad del clustering jerrquico
silhouette_hclust <- silhouette(hclust_clusters, dist_matrix)
sil_score_hclust <- mean(silhouette_hclust[,3])

# 5. Imprimir resultados
cat("\nComparacin de Algoritmos de Clustering:\n")
## 
## Comparacin de Algoritmos de Clustering:
cat("\nK-means:")
## 
## K-means:
cat("\n- Nmero de observaciones por cluster:\n")
## 
## - Nmero de observaciones por cluster:
print(table(kmeans_result$cluster))
## 
##    1    2    3    4 
## 1315  796  873 2513
cat("\n- Coeficiente de silueta promedio:", round(sil_score_kmeans, 3))
## 
## - Coeficiente de silueta promedio: 0.145
cat("\n\nClustering Jerrquico (muestra de", sample_size, "observaciones):")
## 
## 
## Clustering Jerrquico (muestra de 1000 observaciones):
cat("\n- Nmero de observaciones por cluster:\n")
## 
## - Nmero de observaciones por cluster:
print(table(hclust_clusters))
## hclust_clusters
##   1   2   3   4 
## 572 114 116 198
cat("\n- Coeficiente de silueta promedio:", round(sil_score_hclust, 3))
## 
## - Coeficiente de silueta promedio: 0.105
# 6. Visualizar clusters k-means (usando las dos primeras componentes principales)
pca_result <- prcomp(movies_scaled)
cluster_plot <- data.frame(
  PC1 = pca_result$x[,1],
  PC2 = pca_result$x[,2],
  Cluster = as.factor(kmeans_result$cluster)
)

ggplot(cluster_plot, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = Cluster)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Visualizacin de Clusters K-means",
       x = "Primera Componente Principal",
       y = "Segunda Componente Principal")
